caption: I did try this place. This is my second time to eat here. The food is so good. The taste is really Shanghai flavor. It will be my favorite restaurant.

I've eaten here before and the food was really good. This time I ordered new things, two soups (winter melon and jumbo shrimp) and a noodle dish (Scallion Sauce Over Boiled Shanghai Noodles). They were all bad to the point where I couldn't eat more than a bite. The soup basically tasted like slightly flavored water. The noodles tasted like noodles with just soy sauce. Also the shrimp tasted off (ammonia-like). I found this surprising since most of the food I've eaten here in the past was really really good - like just a week before. Either these particular dishes are not good, or maybe there was a new chef working today... I don't know... Based on the bad shrimp, I question the quality of their food... Don't think I'll be returning to this joint unfortunately.

They need to add more soy sauce and sugar to make the flavor stronger.  I really Hope they can change the chef back, cuz this is really not an authentic Shanghai Food for me anymore. It was one of many little Chinese restaurants in Cambridge, conveniently located just out side of Central Square Station.  As the name states, it serves mainly Shanghainese cuisine, and as such I ordered stirred fried Chinese rice cake, the wok temperature was controlled just right and the rice cake tasted soft with a slight taste of burned flavor, which makes it great.  The highlight of the meal was the Sweet and Sour Lotus Roots, which I had it many times before but never presented in this manner, it was almost like a Michelin star restaurant style presentation, but pretty okay on the taste. I felt the slices were cut a bit too big, hard to bite on, and the sweet and sour sauce hardened after the dish was put on the table, overall, it was an interesting presentation and okay taste.  Most importantly, I want to note the service of staff there, they don’t smile, just stop by and drop dishes in your table, and asks if we are finished when we have half of a dish still left and eating. So if you are more of a service oriented person, this restaurant is not for you.  🍡Must order🍡  - Sweet and sour lotus root - Stir fried Chinese rice cake  📜Score (five star scale):  🏝Environment: ⭐️⭐️  👍Services:  ⭐️⭐️  🍽Taste:  ⭐️⭐️⭐️  💰Price: ~USD20-30/person

(Translated by Google) As a Shanghainese, I can barely accept the dishes here. The chef does not exactly follow the cooking method of this set of dishes, it seems to be a fusion of Jiangsu and Zhejiang cuisine and Cantonese cuisine. For example, rice should use lard and bacon, but the chef uses bacon and sausage. Although not unpleasant, this is not what Shanghai cuisine should have. As for my expectant Xiaolongbao, I was very disappointed. Dead noodles + white meat is indeed an authentic Shanghai practice. At this point, it is much better than other people who hold Suzhou soup dumplings and Wuxi small cages to hang sheep's heads and sell dog meat. But the soup in the steamed buns I ate was absorbed by the noodles, and the inside of the noodles became paste-like. The taste and taste were really uncomfortable. If you judge this restaurant by the standard of this dish, it will definitely fail. But considering that this is the United States, it can barely pass. The service experience is average. Seats can only be reserved for more than 4 people, and can only be reserved at three points in time. You can refer to their official website. There are a lot of people for dinner and few seats. Basically you have to wait about 20 minutes. Hope to broaden the facade or open the reservation.  (Original) 作为一个上海人，勉强可以接受这里的菜品。厨师并不完全依照本帮菜的烹饪方式，似乎是融合了江浙菜与粤菜的烹调方式。例如菜饭，应该使用猪油和咸肉，但厨师却用了腊肉和腊肠。虽然不难吃，但这不是上海菜该有的味道。至于我满怀期待的小笼包，则让我很失望。死面皮+白肉确实是正宗的上海做法，在这一点上比别的拿着苏州汤包、无锡小笼来挂羊头卖狗肉的要好不少。但是我吃到的小笼包里汤汁被面皮吸收，面皮内部变得像浆糊一样，口感和味道上实在是让人不敢恭维。如果以本帮菜的标准来评判这家店，那肯定是不及格的。不过考虑到这里是美国，勉强可以及格。 在服务体验上表现得一般。4人以上才可以预定座位，且只能在三个时间点预定，可以去参考他们的官网。晚餐人很多，而座位又少，基本上要等20分钟左右。希望可以拓宽门面或者开放预定。

Very tasty food! The "thumbs up" and "red pepper" symbols on the menu guided our decision making as we figured out what to order for a late night dinner.  We got here around 8:30pm on a Thursday night and the line was still out to the door. Fortunately it was moving pretty quick as people finished up their meals for the night. We saw an awkward situation when the hostess seated two separate parties at the same table, despite the fact that there were other tables opening up soon and not much of a line left. It's a small restaurant so I wouldn't be surprised if that's common practice during the busy hours.  After about 20 minutes, we were seated and the waitress quickly brought out some hot tea. The menu was easy to navigate and, like I said before, the symbols made it easy to decide what to order. The Shanghai Shrimp w/Chef's Special Sauce was a burst of flavor to my taste buds! The Yu Xiang Shredded Pork was pretty good too, though it had a bit of a kick and the bamboo masked the taste of the pork. The portion size was a little disappointing; it would be nice to have more food considering we ordered four plates for three people and we managed to wipe clean each dish!  Yummy food and good service- I will be back!

I came to the United States 10 years ago from Shanghai. This is the first restaurant ever that made me homesick.  Sweet and Sour rib: This is NOT the Americanized Sweet and Sour rib! Nor are these the normal sweet and sour rib you'll find in any Chinese Restaurant (in fact I've never found it anywhere else). This is the real deal, it tastes like, well, home......  Steamed Dumplings: I am extremely picky about Steamed Dumplings, because I grew up eating the best ones in Shanghai. The steamed dumplings here are comparable to that famous dumpling place in New York, and arguably more authentic. You can't ask for more in the U.S.  Salty Soy Milk: This soy milk comes with mini shrimp, pickled vegetable, Chinese fried doe (You Tiao) in it, and is salty and a bit spicy, just the way it should be.  I've been there three times now, and honestly, not every dish I ordered was satisfactory (keep in mind that I cook better myself than half of the Chinese restaurants in town). However, I have had way more pleasant surprises at this place than at anywhere else in Boston.  Warning: The lines can get really long really fast, so go early or book a table ahead of time!!!
